const faqs = [
  { q: 'What actually causes dandruff?', a: 'Most dandruff is driven by Malassezia, a yeast that lives on every scalp but overgrows in some people, accelerating skin turnover into visible flakes. That is why medicated antifungal shampoos work where regular "gentle" shampoos don’t — the target is the yeast, not dirt.' },
  { q: 'How often should I use anti-dandruff shampoo?', a: 'Start with two to three washes a week, leaving the lather on the scalp for 3–5 minutes before rinsing — the most commonly skipped step. Once flaking is controlled, drop to once a week for maintenance; stopping entirely usually brings dandruff back within weeks.' },
  { q: 'Why is my dandruff worse in winter in Pakistan?', a: 'Cold dry air, hot showers, and heavier oiling all tip the scalp environment in the yeast’s favour, which is why flaking peaks from November to February in most of Pakistan. Keep a medicated shampoo in rotation through winter rather than starting after flakes appear.' },
  { q: 'When should I see a dermatologist instead?', a: 'If 6–8 weeks of consistent medicated shampooing hasn’t controlled it, or you have thick scaly plaques, intense itching, redness spreading beyond the hairline, or hair loss in patches — those point to seborrheic dermatitis, psoriasis, or fungal infection needing prescription treatment.' },
  { q: 'Does hair oiling help or worsen dandruff?', a: 'Usually worsens it. Malassezia feeds on oils, so leaving mustard or coconut oil on an already-flaky scalp overnight effectively feeds the cause. If oiling is part of your routine, apply briefly before washing rather than leaving it on overnight.' },
];
